1
00:00:04,440 --> 00:00:05,480
(MACHINERY CLICKING)

2
00:00:18,560 --> 00:00:19,560
Listen!

3
00:00:21,080 --> 00:00:22,200
Question.

4
00:00:22,760 --> 00:00:26,840
Why do we talk out loud when we know

5
00:00:31,040 --> 00:00:32,240
we're alone?

6
00:00:34,520 --> 00:00:35,680
Conjecture.

7
00:00:37,800 --> 00:00:40,000
Because we know we're not.

8
00:00:42,880 --> 00:00:46,360
Evolution perfects survival skills.

9
00:00:50,000 --> 00:00:51,960
There are perfect hunters.

10
00:00:54,040 --> 00:00:55,080
(ROARING)

11
00:01:00,960 --> 00:01:03,080
There is perfect defence.

12
00:01:08,720 --> 00:01:10,240
Question.

13
00:01:10,320 --> 00:01:13,600
Why is there no such thing
as perfect hiding?

14
00:01:16,040 --> 00:01:18,480
Answer. How would you know?

15
00:01:18,560 --> 00:01:21,480
Logically, if evolution
were to perfect a creature

16
00:01:21,600 --> 00:01:24,600
whose primary skill
were to hide from view,

17
00:01:25,480 --> 00:01:26,760
how could you know it existed?

18
00:01:26,840 --> 00:01:29,520
It could be with us every second
and we would never know.

19
00:01:30,040 --> 00:01:31,600
How would you detect it,

20
00:01:32,000 --> 00:01:33,600
even sense it...

21
00:01:37,680 --> 00:01:40,760
...except in those moments

22
00:01:41,240 --> 00:01:43,080
when, for no clear reason,

23
00:01:44,560 --> 00:01:46,200
you choose to speak aloud?

24
00:01:48,200 --> 00:01:50,840
What would such a creature want?

25
00:01:52,320 --> 00:01:53,880
What would it do?

26
00:01:55,600 --> 00:01:56,800
Well?

27
00:01:57,520 --> 00:02:00,280
(LOUDLY) What would you do? (ECHOES)

28
00:02:00,720 --> 00:02:01,760
(LAUGHS)

29
00:02:08,000 --> 00:02:09,040
(CHALK ROLLS)

30
00:02:20,280 --> 00:02:22,880
(DOCTOR WHO THEME)

31
00:03:00,920 --> 00:03:02,080
(EXHALES)

32
00:03:04,880 --> 00:03:06,920
(INDISTINCT TALKING AND LAUGHTER)

33
00:03:13,080 --> 00:03:14,120
(EXHALES)

34
00:03:20,320 --> 00:03:21,480
-Hey.
-Hey.

35
00:03:21,840 --> 00:03:22,880
Sorry.

36
00:03:26,720 --> 00:03:28,240
So the famous drink at last.

37
00:03:28,640 --> 00:03:32,960
Yeah. Took a bit of time,
family stuff, but here we are.

38
00:03:33,040 --> 00:03:34,320
Dinner, in fact.

39
00:03:34,400 --> 00:03:36,400
Yeah, straight to dinner.

40
00:03:36,600 --> 00:03:38,200
I like a man who moves fast.

41
00:03:38,280 --> 00:03:41,280
Yeah? I might go straight for extras.

42
00:03:44,120 --> 00:03:46,880
Afters. Dessert.

43
00:03:46,960 --> 00:03:50,280
-Yes, I know, I know, dessert. Gotcha.
-Straight to dessert.

44
00:03:54,360 --> 00:03:57,720
So, um... How was your day?

45
00:03:57,800 --> 00:03:59,720
Good. You know...

46
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:01,400
Teaching.

47
00:04:01,480 --> 00:04:03,360
-Yep, teaching.
-Teaching, teaching.

48
00:04:03,440 --> 00:04:04,560
Totally teaching.

49
00:04:04,640 --> 00:04:07,120
-We probably shouldn't talk about work.
-God, yeah!

50
00:04:07,200 --> 00:04:08,360
(BOTH LAUGHING)

51
00:04:11,600 --> 00:04:13,480
Though, do you take Courtney
for anything?

52
00:04:18,600 --> 00:04:19,920
Are you serious?

53
00:04:21,160 --> 00:04:23,280
She said she couldn't
concentrate on her work

54
00:04:23,360 --> 00:04:26,440
because my face was too wide.

55
00:04:27,280 --> 00:04:29,760
-Wide?
-I could kill that girl some days.

56
00:04:29,840 --> 00:04:32,160
-Me, too.
-And from you, that means something.

57
00:04:33,400 --> 00:04:34,440
Sorry?

58
00:04:39,840 --> 00:04:41,680
I dug 23 wells.

59
00:04:41,760 --> 00:04:43,960
-I'm sorry?
-Twenty-three wells.

60
00:04:44,040 --> 00:04:45,840
When I was a soldier. Twenty-three!

61
00:04:46,280 --> 00:04:49,360
-Okay. Good. Good wells.
-Yeah, they were good, actually.

62
00:04:49,440 --> 00:04:51,280
I'm not doubting
the quality of your wells.

63
00:04:51,360 --> 00:04:53,880
Whole villages saved.
Actual towns full of people.

64
00:04:53,960 --> 00:04:55,920
People I didn't shoot.
People I kept safe!

65
00:04:56,000 --> 00:04:59,040
-Okay. Point taken. Seriously.
-So why doesn't that ever get mentioned?

66
00:04:59,120 --> 00:05:01,680
I'm sorry I didn't mention
your 23 wells!

67
00:05:02,000 --> 00:05:03,800
-WAITER: Excuse me.
-Sorry.

68
00:05:03,880 --> 00:05:06,040
WAITER: Uh, water for the table?

69
00:05:06,400 --> 00:05:07,920
Don't you worry,
he'll probably dig for it!

70
00:05:13,840 --> 00:05:15,040
(LAUGHS)

71
00:05:15,120 --> 00:05:16,480
Sorry.

72
00:05:16,560 --> 00:05:17,560
It's okay.

73
00:05:17,640 --> 00:05:20,640
-Sensitive subject.
-Yes. Can slightly see that.

74
00:05:21,520 --> 00:05:24,080
Sometimes people like you
get the wrong end of the stick.

75
00:05:24,160 --> 00:05:25,280
People like me?

76
00:05:29,160 --> 00:05:30,680
I wasn't making assumptions about you.

77
00:05:30,760 --> 00:05:32,280
That really is exactly
what you were doing.

78
00:05:32,360 --> 00:05:33,520
You were making assumptions about me!

79
00:05:33,600 --> 00:05:35,480
-I made a joke.
-A not-funny joke.

80
00:05:35,800 --> 00:05:37,560
Yeah, well, do you know
what I'm making now?

81
00:05:37,640 --> 00:05:39,320
-A fuss?
-An exit.

82
00:05:44,960 --> 00:05:46,160
(SIGHS)

83
00:05:55,480 --> 00:05:58,560
-You'll just have to squeeze through.
-Doctor?

84
00:05:58,640 --> 00:06:00,680
Why do you have three mirrors?
Why don't you just turn your head?

85
00:06:00,760 --> 00:06:04,080
-What are you doing in here?
-You said you had a date.

86
00:06:04,160 --> 00:06:06,640
I thought I'd better hide in the bedroom
in case you brought him home.

87
00:06:06,720 --> 00:06:07,960
Bit early, aren't you?

88
00:06:08,040 --> 00:06:11,400
Did it all go wrong?
Or is this good by your standards?

89
00:06:12,040 --> 00:06:14,560
It was a disaster and I'm extremely
upset about it, since you didn't ask.

90
00:06:15,040 --> 00:06:18,200
Fine! I need you, for a thing.

91
00:06:18,280 --> 00:06:19,280
I can't.

92
00:06:19,360 --> 00:06:20,960
Oh, of course you can.
Come on, you're free.

93
00:06:21,040 --> 00:06:22,360
More than usually free, in fact.

94
00:06:22,680 --> 00:06:25,200
No, it's just possible
that I might get a phone call.

95
00:06:25,280 --> 00:06:26,560
From the date guy?

96
00:06:26,640 --> 00:06:29,160
It's too late.
You've taken your make-up off.

97
00:06:29,440 --> 00:06:31,920
No, I haven't.
I'm still wearing my make-up.

98
00:06:32,120 --> 00:06:33,480
Oh, well, okay,
well, you probably just missed a bit.

99
00:06:33,560 --> 00:06:35,040
Come on, come on, come on, come on!

100
00:06:40,920 --> 00:06:42,320
I haven't actually said yes.

101
00:06:42,400 --> 00:06:43,880
Yes, you know,
sometimes when you talk to yourself,

102
00:06:43,960 --> 00:06:45,000
-what if you're not?
-Not what?

103
00:06:45,080 --> 00:06:46,520
What if it's not you you're talking to?

104
00:06:46,800 --> 00:06:50,720
Proposition. What if no one
is ever really alone?

105
00:06:50,800 --> 00:06:53,040
What if every single living being
has a companion,

106
00:06:53,120 --> 00:06:55,480
a silent passenger, a shadow?

107
00:06:56,240 --> 00:06:58,040
What if the prickle
on the back of your neck

108
00:06:58,120 --> 00:06:59,720
is the breath of something
close behind you?

109
00:07:00,320 --> 00:07:01,960
How long have you been travelling alone?

110
00:07:02,840 --> 00:07:04,040
Perhaps I never have.

111
00:07:08,880 --> 00:07:09,880
It looks like your handwriting.

112
00:07:09,960 --> 00:07:12,000
Well, I couldn't have written it
and forgotten, could I?

113
00:07:12,080 --> 00:07:15,040
(CHUCKLES) Have you met you?
What's all this?

114
00:07:15,120 --> 00:07:17,760
Dreams. Accounts of dreams by
different people, all through history.

115
00:07:18,000 --> 00:07:20,360
-You see, I have a theory.
-I'll bet you have. What theory?

116
00:07:20,440 --> 00:07:23,080
I think everybody,
at some point in their lives,

117
00:07:23,160 --> 00:07:25,360
has the exact same nightmare.

118
00:07:28,320 --> 00:07:31,480
You wake up, or you think you do,

119
00:07:31,560 --> 00:07:34,680
and there's someone in the dark,
someone close,

120
00:07:34,760 --> 00:07:36,080
or you think there might be.

121
00:07:36,640 --> 00:07:37,680
(BREATHING DEEPLY)

122
00:07:37,760 --> 00:07:40,240
So you sit up and turn on the light.

123
00:07:40,960 --> 00:07:43,560
And the room looks different at night.

124
00:07:44,120 --> 00:07:47,920
It ticks and creaks and breathes.

125
00:07:49,520 --> 00:07:51,840
And you tell yourself
there's nobody there,

126
00:07:51,920 --> 00:07:53,920
nobody watching, nobody listening,

127
00:07:54,000 --> 00:07:56,320
nobody there at all.

128
00:07:58,400 --> 00:08:00,240
And you very nearly believe it.

129
00:08:02,800 --> 00:08:05,720
You really, really try.

130
00:08:07,160 --> 00:08:08,400
And then...

131
00:08:08,480 --> 00:08:10,000
(HISSING)

132
00:08:12,440 --> 00:08:13,480
(GASPING)

133
00:08:16,880 --> 00:08:19,440
There are accounts of that dream
throughout human history,

134
00:08:19,520 --> 00:08:21,480
time and time again, the same dream.

135
00:08:21,560 --> 00:08:24,320
Now, there is a very obvious
question I'm about to ask you.

136
00:08:24,400 --> 00:08:25,640
-Do you know what it is?
-Have you had that dream?

137
00:08:25,720 --> 00:08:27,040
Exactly.

138
00:08:27,120 --> 00:08:28,800
No, that was me asking you,
have you had that dream?

139
00:08:28,880 --> 00:08:30,480
-I asked first.
-No, I did.

140
00:08:30,560 --> 00:08:31,840
You really didn't.

141
00:08:32,360 --> 00:08:35,880
Okay, yeah, probably. Yes.

142
00:08:35,960 --> 00:08:37,440
But everybody dreams about
something under the bed.

143
00:08:37,520 --> 00:08:38,520
Why?

144
00:08:42,960 --> 00:08:45,320
Just hold on tight.
If anything bites, let it.

145
00:08:46,240 --> 00:08:48,320
-What is it?
-Tardis telepathic interface.

146
00:08:48,400 --> 00:08:50,640
You're now in mental contact
with the Tardis.

147
00:08:50,720 --> 00:08:52,480
-So don't think anything rude.
-Why not?

148
00:08:52,560 --> 00:08:54,520
It might end up on all of the screens.

149
00:08:54,600 --> 00:08:57,040
The Tardis is extrapolating
your entire timeline,

150
00:08:57,120 --> 00:08:59,400
from the moment of your birth
to the moment of your death.

151
00:08:59,480 --> 00:09:01,480
Which I do not need a preview of.

152
00:09:01,560 --> 00:09:04,000
I'm turning off the safeguards
and navigation,

153
00:09:04,720 --> 00:09:06,000
slaving the Tardis to you.

154
00:09:08,200 --> 00:09:09,960
Focus on the dream,

155
00:09:10,040 --> 00:09:13,760
focus on the details,
picture them, feel them.

156
00:09:13,840 --> 00:09:16,280
The Tardis will track on
your subconscious

157
00:09:16,360 --> 00:09:18,200
and extract the relevant information.

158
00:09:18,280 --> 00:09:21,680
It should be able to home in
on the moment in your timeline

159
00:09:21,760 --> 00:09:23,800
when you first had that dream.

160
00:09:23,880 --> 00:09:25,640
And then, we'll see.

161
00:09:27,920 --> 00:09:29,080
What will we see?

162
00:09:29,760 --> 00:09:31,640
What's under your bed.

163
00:09:36,160 --> 00:09:37,200
Ooh!

164
00:09:37,280 --> 00:09:39,040
(METALLIC HUMMING)

165
00:09:39,800 --> 00:09:42,080
Okay, now, don't get distracted.

166
00:09:42,640 --> 00:09:45,120
Remember, you are flying a time machine.

167
00:09:45,200 --> 00:09:47,160
(METALLIC HUMMING CONTINUES)

168
00:09:49,280 --> 00:09:50,880
-(MOBILE RINGING)
-(GASPS)

169
00:09:51,040 --> 00:09:54,840
No, no. Don't you get...
No, don't. Don't, don't.

170
00:09:54,920 --> 00:09:56,280
Just ignore it.

171
00:09:57,080 --> 00:09:58,080
(MOBILE CLATTERS, STOPS RINGING)

172
00:10:00,320 --> 00:10:02,160
Okay, that's good.

173
00:10:03,360 --> 00:10:06,040
That worked, we're here.

174
00:10:06,120 --> 00:10:07,680
Sorry, I think I got distracted.

175
00:10:07,760 --> 00:10:10,520
No, no, no, no, no. The date's fine.

176
00:10:11,800 --> 00:10:13,080
-Come on!
-Come on where?

177
00:10:14,600 --> 00:10:15,640
Your childhood.

178
00:10:22,160 --> 00:10:23,200
(GRUNTS)

179
00:10:29,480 --> 00:10:31,480
The West Country Children's Home.

180
00:10:34,800 --> 00:10:39,400
Gloucester. By the ozone level
and the drains, mid-'90s.

181
00:10:40,200 --> 00:10:42,040
You must have been here
when you had the dream.

182
00:10:43,120 --> 00:10:44,600
Never been to Gloucester in my life

183
00:10:44,680 --> 00:10:46,440
and I've never lived
in a children's home.

184
00:10:46,680 --> 00:10:47,960
You've probably just forgotten.

185
00:10:48,040 --> 00:10:50,320
Have you seen the size of human
brains? They're hilarious.

186
00:10:50,400 --> 00:10:53,720
Little you must be in here somewhere,
with your little brain.

187
00:10:53,800 --> 00:10:55,440
Isn't it bad if I meet myself?

188
00:10:55,760 --> 00:10:57,480
It is potentially catastrophic.

189
00:10:57,560 --> 00:10:59,680
So why did you bring me out here?

190
00:10:59,760 --> 00:11:01,240
I was still talking,
I needed someone to nod,

191
00:11:01,320 --> 00:11:02,920
probably best for you to wait
in the Tardis.

192
00:11:03,000 --> 00:11:04,040
Doctor...

193
00:11:04,120 --> 00:11:05,720
See you in a minute. Tardis.

194
00:11:06,280 --> 00:11:07,360
Doctor!

195
00:11:09,200 --> 00:11:11,440
If I had have been distracted,
what would have happened?

196
00:11:11,520 --> 00:11:14,040
We would probably have ended up
in the wrong place.

197
00:11:14,120 --> 00:11:17,360
But don't think we have,
because the time zone's right.

198
00:11:17,440 --> 00:11:18,640
I won't be long.

199
00:11:33,400 --> 00:11:35,120
BOY: What are you doing down there?

200
00:11:35,960 --> 00:11:36,960
Nothing.

201
00:11:37,880 --> 00:11:39,840
Uh... I'm just...

202
00:11:43,200 --> 00:11:44,200
What's your name?

203
00:11:44,280 --> 00:11:46,200
-Rupert.
-Oh. Okay.

204
00:11:47,000 --> 00:11:48,000
Hello, Rupert.

205
00:11:48,080 --> 00:11:51,160
Rupert Pink. It's a stupid name.

206
00:11:51,240 --> 00:11:52,480
No, it isn't.

207
00:11:53,360 --> 00:11:54,880
I know somebody called Pink.

208
00:11:54,960 --> 00:11:57,200
I meant Rupert. I'm going to change it.

209
00:11:57,760 --> 00:11:58,960
Why are you awake?

210
00:12:01,760 --> 00:12:03,440
Are you scared?

211
00:12:04,880 --> 00:12:06,160
(HUMMING)

212
00:12:12,120 --> 00:12:13,120
(TV PLAYING, MUFFLED)

213
00:12:14,280 --> 00:12:15,440
(DOOR OPENS)

214
00:12:18,920 --> 00:12:20,200
MAN: How did you get in?

215
00:12:20,440 --> 00:12:21,760
Your door must be faulty.

216
00:12:28,840 --> 00:12:30,040
An inspection?

217
00:12:31,960 --> 00:12:34,000
-It's 2:00 in the morning.
-When better?

218
00:12:34,920 --> 00:12:36,360
Do you always work here nights?

219
00:12:37,120 --> 00:12:38,160
Most nights, yes.

220
00:12:39,560 --> 00:12:41,440
Ever end up talking to yourself?

221
00:12:43,040 --> 00:12:45,800
All the time. It's this place.

222
00:12:47,360 --> 00:12:48,520
You can't help it.

223
00:12:50,720 --> 00:12:52,040
What about your coffee?

224
00:12:54,080 --> 00:12:55,120
My coffee?

225
00:12:57,680 --> 00:13:01,120
Sometimes do you put it down
and look round

226
00:13:01,880 --> 00:13:03,280
and it's not there?

227
00:13:04,960 --> 00:13:06,880
-Everybody does that.
-Yes.

228
00:13:07,440 --> 00:13:08,720
Everybody.

229
00:13:09,400 --> 00:13:10,440
(TV TURNS OFF)

230
00:13:11,360 --> 00:13:12,720
Who turned your telly off?

231
00:13:13,080 --> 00:13:15,320
It does that. It...

232
00:13:17,480 --> 00:13:18,600
just goes off.

233
00:13:32,880 --> 00:13:34,000
Hmm.

234
00:13:35,800 --> 00:13:36,840
(DOOR CREAKS)

235
00:13:55,160 --> 00:13:56,280
Hello.

236
00:13:57,160 --> 00:13:58,680
Hello.

237
00:14:00,960 --> 00:14:02,000
Nice room.

238
00:14:06,360 --> 00:14:09,280
You know, you should have
more than one chair.

239
00:14:09,360 --> 00:14:11,160
What do you do when people come round?

240
00:14:11,240 --> 00:14:12,320
RUPERT: Sit on the bed.

241
00:14:14,160 --> 00:14:16,200
CLARA: Why aren't you
sitting on it, then?

242
00:14:18,720 --> 00:14:20,600
Do you think that there's
something underneath it?

243
00:14:22,280 --> 00:14:23,320
Hey.

244
00:14:24,920 --> 00:14:27,600
Everyone thinks that sometimes.

245
00:14:27,680 --> 00:14:30,400
-That's just how people think at night.
-Why?

246
00:14:32,720 --> 00:14:34,000
Did you have a dream,

247
00:14:34,560 --> 00:14:36,200
a hand grabbing your foot?

248
00:14:37,240 --> 00:14:38,600
You have, haven't you?

249
00:14:39,800 --> 00:14:41,240
You've had that exact dream.

250
00:14:41,320 --> 00:14:42,560
How did you know?

251
00:14:44,840 --> 00:14:47,040
Do you know why dreams
are called dreams?

252
00:14:47,120 --> 00:14:49,000
-Why?
-Because they're not real.

253
00:14:50,480 --> 00:14:52,760
If they were, they wouldn't need a name.

254
00:14:55,600 --> 00:14:56,880
What are you doing?

255
00:15:00,640 --> 00:15:02,880
-Do you know what's under there?
-What?

256
00:15:02,960 --> 00:15:04,280
Me!

257
00:15:05,960 --> 00:15:08,600
Come on! It's perfectly safe.

258
00:15:16,480 --> 00:15:17,760
See?

259
00:15:17,840 --> 00:15:19,880
Nobody here. Except us.

260
00:15:19,960 --> 00:15:21,760
Sometimes I hear noises.

261
00:15:22,600 --> 00:15:25,160
It's a house full of people,
of course you hear noises.

262
00:15:25,760 --> 00:15:28,480
-They're all asleep.
-They're all dreaming.

263
00:15:30,400 --> 00:15:31,960
Can you hear dreams?

264
00:15:33,640 --> 00:15:36,440
If you're clever enough,
but they can't harm you.

265
00:15:37,960 --> 00:15:40,560
You know, sometimes we think
there's something behind us

266
00:15:40,640 --> 00:15:43,960
and the space under your bed is
what's behind you at night.

267
00:15:44,040 --> 00:15:46,760
Simple as that.
There's nothing to be afraid of.

268
00:15:47,200 --> 00:15:48,480
(BED CREAKS)

269
00:15:49,160 --> 00:15:50,600
(RUPERT BREATHING HEAVILY)

270
00:15:58,200 --> 00:16:00,680
-(WHISPERS) Who else is in this room?
-Nobody.

271
00:16:04,120 --> 00:16:06,520
-Someone must have come in.
-Nobody came in.

272
00:16:22,720 --> 00:16:24,000
CLARA: Hello?

273
00:16:36,000 --> 00:16:37,280
Who's this?

274
00:16:37,560 --> 00:16:39,360
This is a friend of yours
playing a game.

275
00:16:46,320 --> 00:16:49,600
Playing a trick, are you, hey,
a little trick on Rupert here?

276
00:16:51,360 --> 00:16:52,640
(BED CREAKING)

277
00:16:58,960 --> 00:17:01,600
Okay. It's not funny this, you know.

278
00:17:05,360 --> 00:17:06,480
Where is he?

279
00:17:06,840 --> 00:17:07,880
Doctor?

280
00:17:07,960 --> 00:17:08,960
DOCTOR: I can't find him.
Can you find him?

281
00:17:09,040 --> 00:17:10,520
CLARA: Find who?
DOCTOR: Wally.

282
00:17:10,600 --> 00:17:12,960
-Wally?
-He's nowhere in this book.

283
00:17:13,240 --> 00:17:14,760
RUPERT: It's not a Where's Wally? one.

284
00:17:15,400 --> 00:17:17,760
Well, how would you know? Maybe you
just haven't found him yet.

285
00:17:17,840 --> 00:17:20,080
-He's not in every book.
-Really?

286
00:17:20,480 --> 00:17:22,600
Well, that's a few years of my life
I'll be needing back.

287
00:17:23,960 --> 00:17:25,000
Are you scared?

288
00:17:28,120 --> 00:17:30,280
The thing on the bed, whatever it is,

289
00:17:31,320 --> 00:17:33,000
look at it. Does it scare you?

290
00:17:33,320 --> 00:17:34,640
-Yes.
-Well, that's good.

291
00:17:35,200 --> 00:17:36,360
Want to know why that's good?

292
00:17:36,720 --> 00:17:39,920
-Why?
-Let me tell you about scared.

293
00:17:40,080 --> 00:17:41,120
(HEART BEATING)

294
00:17:41,200 --> 00:17:44,000
Your heart is beating so hard

295
00:17:44,080 --> 00:17:45,520
I can feel it through your hands.

296
00:17:45,600 --> 00:17:49,120
There's so much blood and oxygen
pumping through your brain,

297
00:17:49,200 --> 00:17:50,840
it's like rocket fuel.

298
00:17:50,920 --> 00:17:55,440
Right now, you could run faster
and you could fight harder,

299
00:17:55,520 --> 00:17:58,560
you could jump higher
than ever in your life,

300
00:17:58,640 --> 00:18:03,080
and you are so alert
it's like you can slow down time.

301
00:18:03,760 --> 00:18:07,920
What's wrong with scared?
Scared is a superpower.

302
00:18:08,000 --> 00:18:09,240
It's your superpower.

303
00:18:09,320 --> 00:18:13,080
There is danger in this room
and guess what? It's you.

304
00:18:13,160 --> 00:18:14,240
Do you feel it?

305
00:18:16,640 --> 00:18:17,720
Do you think he feels it?

306
00:18:18,560 --> 00:18:20,880
Do you think he's scared?

307
00:18:21,840 --> 00:18:22,880
Nah!

308
00:18:23,440 --> 00:18:25,680
Loser! Turn your back on him.

309
00:18:26,040 --> 00:18:29,600
-What?
-Yeah, turn your back on him, come on.

310
00:18:30,160 --> 00:18:31,440
You too, Clara.

311
00:18:31,520 --> 00:18:33,160
Clara, your back, now.

312
00:18:35,720 --> 00:18:37,800
Do it, just do it now, turn your back.

313
00:18:40,280 --> 00:18:41,720
Do it now, turn your back.

314
00:18:43,800 --> 00:18:45,360
Lovely view out this window.

315
00:18:45,440 --> 00:18:48,680
CLARA: Yeah. Come and see all the dark.

316
00:18:49,000 --> 00:18:50,960
DOCTOR: The deep and lovely dark.

317
00:18:51,560 --> 00:18:53,640
We'd never see the stars without it.

318
00:18:55,240 --> 00:18:57,320
Now, there are two possibilities.

319
00:18:57,400 --> 00:19:00,200
Possibility one, it's just
one of your friends standing there

320
00:19:00,280 --> 00:19:03,520
and he's playing a joke on you.
Possibility two, it isn't.

321
00:19:03,600 --> 00:19:05,800
So, plan? Plans are good.

322
00:19:08,800 --> 00:19:11,840
DOCTOR: You on the bed,
I'm talking to you now.

323
00:19:11,920 --> 00:19:13,280
Go in peace.

324
00:19:13,920 --> 00:19:15,000
We won't look.

325
00:19:15,720 --> 00:19:16,920
Just go.

326
00:19:17,400 --> 00:19:20,360
If all you want to do is stay
hidden, it's okay. Just leave.

327
00:19:20,600 --> 00:19:21,600
(BREATHING DEEPLY)

328
00:19:31,480 --> 00:19:32,520
Is it gone?

329
00:19:33,520 --> 00:19:36,000
Don't look round, not yet.

330
00:19:36,400 --> 00:19:39,720
-I can't hear anything.
-DOCTOR: Don't look round.

331
00:19:41,000 --> 00:19:43,760
Look away! Look away now!
Don't look at it! Don't look round.

332
00:19:43,840 --> 00:19:45,360
Don't look round.
Don't look at the reflection.

333
00:19:45,440 --> 00:19:46,480
What is it?

334
00:19:46,560 --> 00:19:48,280
DOCTOR: Imagine a thing
that must never be seen.

335
00:19:48,360 --> 00:19:50,240
-What would it do if you saw it?
-I don't know.

336
00:19:50,320 --> 00:19:52,520
-Neither do I. Close your eyes.
-RUPERT: What?

337
00:19:52,600 --> 00:19:54,280
Close your eyes. You, too, Clara.

338
00:19:54,360 --> 00:19:55,440
Give it what it wants.

339
00:19:56,640 --> 00:19:59,080
Prove to it
that you're not going to look at it.

340
00:19:59,160 --> 00:20:02,360
Make a promise. Promise
you're never going to look at it.

341
00:20:02,440 --> 00:20:03,840
I promise never to look.

342
00:20:09,160 --> 00:20:10,720
DOCTOR: The breath on the back
of your neck,

343
00:20:12,880 --> 00:20:14,880
like your hairs standing on end,

344
00:20:15,960 --> 00:20:19,440
that means don't look round.

345
00:20:19,520 --> 00:20:21,200
(DOOR SLAMS SHUT)

346
00:20:23,280 --> 00:20:24,600
Gone.

347
00:20:25,760 --> 00:20:26,880
Gone.

348
00:20:27,960 --> 00:20:29,800
He took my bedspread.

349
00:20:30,520 --> 00:20:33,360
Oh, the human race.
You're never happy, are you?

350
00:20:34,040 --> 00:20:35,800
-Am I safe now?
-DOCTOR: Nobody's safe,

351
00:20:35,880 --> 00:20:40,080
especially not at night,
in the dark. Anything can get you,

352
00:20:40,160 --> 00:20:41,960
you're all the way up here,
you're all alone.

353
00:20:43,720 --> 00:20:46,120
-What was that for?
-Shut up, leave this to me.

354
00:20:47,920 --> 00:20:49,800
-These yours?
-RUPERT: They're the home's.

355
00:20:50,920 --> 00:20:53,760
-They're yours now.
-People don't need to be lied to.

356
00:20:53,840 --> 00:20:56,160
People don't need to be scared
by a big grey-haired stick insect

357
00:20:56,240 --> 00:20:58,200
but here you are. Stay still, shut up.

358
00:20:59,840 --> 00:21:00,960
See what I'm doing?

359
00:21:02,760 --> 00:21:03,920
This is your army.

360
00:21:04,000 --> 00:21:05,760
-Plastic army.
-Sit!

361
00:21:06,560 --> 00:21:09,200
And they're going to guard
under your bed.

362
00:21:10,880 --> 00:21:14,400
See this one? This one's the boss one,

363
00:21:14,480 --> 00:21:16,720
the colonel. He's going to
keep a special eye out.

364
00:21:16,800 --> 00:21:19,400
It's broken, that one.
It doesn't have a gun.

365
00:21:19,480 --> 00:21:20,840
CLARA: That's why he's the boss.

366
00:21:22,560 --> 00:21:24,560
A soldier so brave
he doesn't need a gun.

367
00:21:25,680 --> 00:21:27,680
He can keep the whole world safe.

368
00:21:28,760 --> 00:21:30,640
-What shall we call him?
-Dan.

369
00:21:34,000 --> 00:21:35,200
Sorry?

370
00:21:36,080 --> 00:21:38,400
Dan, the soldier man.
That's what I call him.

371
00:21:38,480 --> 00:21:40,400
Good. Good name.

372
00:21:41,000 --> 00:21:42,320
Yeah.

373
00:21:43,000 --> 00:21:44,960
Would you read me a story?
It'll help me get to sleep.

374
00:21:45,040 --> 00:21:46,080
Sure.

375
00:21:46,160 --> 00:21:47,240
DOCTOR: Once upon a time,

376
00:21:48,240 --> 00:21:49,480
the end.

377
00:21:50,960 --> 00:21:52,200
Dad skills.

378
00:21:57,200 --> 00:22:01,320
So...is it possible
that we just saved that kid

379
00:22:01,400 --> 00:22:03,240
from another kid in a bedspread?

380
00:22:03,320 --> 00:22:04,520
DOCTOR: Entirely possible, yes.

381
00:22:04,600 --> 00:22:08,320
The bigger question is why did
we end up with him and not you?

382
00:22:09,720 --> 00:22:10,800
I got distracted.

383
00:22:10,880 --> 00:22:12,680
But why that particular boy?

384
00:22:12,760 --> 00:22:14,400
You don't have any...

385
00:22:14,480 --> 00:22:16,360
You don't have any kind of connection
with him, do you?

386
00:22:16,440 --> 00:22:18,160
No. No, no, no, of course not.
Why do you ask?

387
00:22:18,240 --> 00:22:20,640
The Tardis was slaved to your timeline.

388
00:22:21,600 --> 00:22:24,200
Theoretically, there should have
been some connection.

389
00:22:24,800 --> 00:22:26,000
Will, um...

390
00:22:27,880 --> 00:22:29,280
Will he remember any of that?

391
00:22:29,800 --> 00:22:31,440
Scrambled his memory,

392
00:22:31,520 --> 00:22:35,200
gave him a big old dream
about being Dan the soldier man.

393
00:22:35,800 --> 00:22:37,080
(SIGHS)

394
00:22:38,240 --> 00:22:39,360
(CLARA WHIMPERS)

395
00:22:42,560 --> 00:22:43,920
Are you okay?

396
00:22:44,240 --> 00:22:45,280
Doctor...

397
00:22:45,680 --> 00:22:47,440
I am sorry to ask and, you know,

398
00:22:47,520 --> 00:22:49,760
I realise this is probably
against the laws of time

399
00:22:49,840 --> 00:22:51,680
or summat, um...

400
00:22:53,280 --> 00:22:54,680
Could you do me a favour?

401
00:23:06,320 --> 00:23:07,920
Is that what I look like from the back?

402
00:23:08,520 --> 00:23:09,640
DOCTOR: It's fine.

403
00:23:09,880 --> 00:23:11,200
CLARA: I was thinking it was good.

404
00:23:11,800 --> 00:23:12,880
Really?

405
00:23:34,920 --> 00:23:36,040
CLARA: Sorry.

406
00:23:37,040 --> 00:23:38,120
Hey.

407
00:23:44,160 --> 00:23:46,600
Hello. I'm Clara Oswald.

408
00:23:46,760 --> 00:23:50,400
I'm a bit tricky sometimes, a bit up
myself and I do not like my surname

409
00:23:50,480 --> 00:23:53,360
but I think that is basically
everything you need to worry about.

410
00:23:57,560 --> 00:24:00,960
Hello, I'm... I'm sorry...

411
00:24:01,040 --> 00:24:03,280
Also, I mouth off when I'm nervous
and I've got a mouth on me.

412
00:24:03,360 --> 00:24:06,240
Seriously, it's got a mind of its
own. I'm worried it wants to go solo.

413
00:24:06,320 --> 00:24:08,880
-I don't know what to say.
-Don't say anything.

414
00:24:08,960 --> 00:24:10,640
Or say something nice.

415
00:24:12,560 --> 00:24:14,440
I like your name.

416
00:24:18,000 --> 00:24:19,200
It's a start.

417
00:24:19,280 --> 00:24:21,360
Oswald. It suits you.

418
00:24:21,440 --> 00:24:23,760
-Drifting now.
-It's better than Pink.

419
00:24:23,840 --> 00:24:26,960
No, Pink... Pink is nice. I like pink.

420
00:24:27,040 --> 00:24:29,960
-You can have it.
-Oh, a bold offer, Mr Pink.

421
00:24:30,040 --> 00:24:32,840
I meant... No... (STAMMERS)

422
00:24:32,920 --> 00:24:34,160
I know, I know.

423
00:24:35,000 --> 00:24:36,600
Why can't I speak today?

424
00:24:36,960 --> 00:24:38,840
It's that foot you're keeping
in your mouth.

425
00:24:38,920 --> 00:24:40,600
Is that where I put it?

426
00:24:40,680 --> 00:24:44,400
Anyway. Clara Pink, too much.

427
00:24:44,760 --> 00:24:46,520
Yeah, it is a bit much.

428
00:24:46,600 --> 00:24:48,120
Mind you, Rupert Pink!

429
00:24:50,120 --> 00:24:51,400
Sorry?

430
00:24:53,000 --> 00:24:54,120
Uh...

431
00:24:54,360 --> 00:24:55,440
(CHUCKLES)

432
00:24:55,960 --> 00:24:58,520
Rupert...Pink. It's not good.

433
00:24:59,000 --> 00:25:00,240
Rupert?

434
00:25:00,600 --> 00:25:02,640
Yeah. That was your name, yeah?

435
00:25:03,680 --> 00:25:08,680
-Who told you that?
-Um, someone in the school.

436
00:25:12,560 --> 00:25:14,040
No, I haven't used that name for years.

437
00:25:14,120 --> 00:25:15,960
I cannot remember who it was...

438
00:25:16,320 --> 00:25:19,240
-Are you making fun of me?
-No! No, no, no. No way!

439
00:25:19,720 --> 00:25:20,760
Is this a joke?

440
00:25:20,840 --> 00:25:23,200
Danny, nothing about this
is any kind of joke!

441
00:25:23,280 --> 00:25:24,320
(DOOR CREAKS)

442
00:25:27,200 --> 00:25:28,320
Where's your coat?

443
00:25:28,720 --> 00:25:31,440
-(EXHALES) My what?
-You put your coat on when you left.

444
00:25:31,520 --> 00:25:33,720
Uh, I'm really sorry. Danny, um,

445
00:25:33,800 --> 00:25:35,920
there is something that I should
probably be honest about.

446
00:25:36,000 --> 00:25:37,560
-How about everything?
-Everything in my case

447
00:25:37,640 --> 00:25:39,160
is actually quite a lot.

448
00:25:40,760 --> 00:25:43,320
-Well, that's weird.
-No, no, it's not weird, not really...

449
00:25:43,400 --> 00:25:44,480
Where are you going?

450
00:25:44,560 --> 00:25:46,840
-I don't do weird.
-Don't go.

451
00:25:47,640 --> 00:25:49,480
Then do something for me.

452
00:25:49,560 --> 00:25:52,680
Tell me the truth, because I know
when people are lying to me.

453
00:25:53,520 --> 00:25:57,040
However weird this thing may be,
just tell me the truth!

454
00:25:57,120 --> 00:25:58,400
It's not weird...

455
00:26:01,640 --> 00:26:03,000
exactly.

456
00:26:05,880 --> 00:26:06,920
I've had enough.

457
00:26:11,680 --> 00:26:12,720
(EXHALES)

458
00:26:31,680 --> 00:26:33,920
I am trying to have a date,

459
00:26:34,000 --> 00:26:37,280
a real-life, inter-human actual date!

460
00:26:37,680 --> 00:26:40,760
It's a normal, nice, everyday,
meeting-up sort of thing.

461
00:26:40,840 --> 00:26:42,800
And I would just like to know,
is there any other way

462
00:26:42,880 --> 00:26:46,400
you can make this any more surreal
than it already is?

463
00:26:49,240 --> 00:26:50,440
Hello.

464
00:26:50,520 --> 00:26:52,360
DOCTOR: Ah, Clara!

465
00:26:53,680 --> 00:26:55,160
Well done, you found her.

466
00:26:56,480 --> 00:26:59,280
Now, this is really a bit strange.

467
00:26:59,360 --> 00:27:00,520
Danny?

468
00:27:01,600 --> 00:27:03,200
What's gone wrong with your face?
It's all eyes!

469
00:27:03,280 --> 00:27:05,640
Why are you all eyes?
Get them under control.

470
00:27:06,120 --> 00:27:10,200
-Uh, who's Danny?
-This is Colonel Orson Pink,

471
00:27:10,280 --> 00:27:12,720
from about a hundred years
into your future.

472
00:27:12,800 --> 00:27:14,280
(CHUCKLES) Orson Pink?

473
00:27:14,880 --> 00:27:17,600
Yeah, I laughed, too. Sorry.

474
00:27:17,680 --> 00:27:21,200
-Do you have any connection with him?
-Connection?

475
00:27:21,280 --> 00:27:25,080
Yes, maybe you're like a distant
relative or something?

476
00:27:25,160 --> 00:27:27,000
(STAMMERS) How would I know?

477
00:27:28,280 --> 00:27:29,880
Right, okay.

478
00:27:29,960 --> 00:27:35,200
Um, well, do you have any
old family photographs of her?

479
00:27:35,280 --> 00:27:39,240
You know, probably quite old
and really fat-looking?

480
00:27:39,320 --> 00:27:40,480
I don't.

481
00:27:44,080 --> 00:27:45,520
How did you find him?

482
00:27:45,600 --> 00:27:47,880
Well, you left a trace in the Tardis
telepathic circuits.

483
00:27:47,960 --> 00:27:50,760
I fired them up again and the Tardis
brought me straight to him.

484
00:27:50,840 --> 00:27:53,120
So he is something to do
with your timeline.

485
00:27:53,200 --> 00:27:54,280
Okay...

486
00:27:54,360 --> 00:27:56,200
And you will never guess
where I found him.

487
00:28:02,960 --> 00:28:04,200
Where are we?

488
00:28:04,280 --> 00:28:05,840
DOCTOR: The end of the road.

489
00:28:05,920 --> 00:28:09,120
This is it, the end of everything.

490
00:28:11,000 --> 00:28:12,280
The last planet.

491
00:28:12,360 --> 00:28:13,440
The end of the universe?

492
00:28:13,520 --> 00:28:15,280
The Tardis isn't supposed
to come this far

493
00:28:15,360 --> 00:28:17,880
but some idiot
turned the safeguards off.

494
00:28:17,960 --> 00:28:19,040
Listen!

495
00:28:21,800 --> 00:28:22,920
To what?

496
00:28:25,640 --> 00:28:26,760
Nothing.

497
00:28:27,200 --> 00:28:28,640
There's nothing to hear.

498
00:28:30,200 --> 00:28:32,200
There's nothing anywhere,

499
00:28:34,360 --> 00:28:35,600
not a breath,

500
00:28:36,800 --> 00:28:39,640
not a slither, not a click or a tick.

501
00:28:39,720 --> 00:28:41,160
All the clocks have stopped.

502
00:28:41,240 --> 00:28:45,600
This is the silence at the end of time.

503
00:28:49,160 --> 00:28:50,240
(CLATTERING)

504
00:28:51,440 --> 00:28:55,200
Then how did he get here?
If he's 100 years in my future...

505
00:28:55,280 --> 00:28:56,720
Pioneer time traveller.

506
00:28:57,320 --> 00:28:58,360
(HUMMING)

507
00:28:59,200 --> 00:29:01,000
Rode the first of the great time shots.

508
00:29:01,080 --> 00:29:03,360
They were supposed to fire him
into the middle of next week.

509
00:29:03,440 --> 00:29:05,160
-What happened?
-He went a bit far.

510
00:29:05,240 --> 00:29:07,400
-A bit?
-A big bit.

511
00:29:07,480 --> 00:29:11,280
Look at him now. Robinson Crusoe
at the end of time itself,

512
00:29:12,200 --> 00:29:14,040
the last man standing in the universe.

513
00:29:14,120 --> 00:29:15,520
I always thought that would be me.

514
00:29:16,040 --> 00:29:17,160
It's not a competition.

515
00:29:17,240 --> 00:29:20,400
I know it's not a competition,
course it isn't.

516
00:29:20,880 --> 00:29:22,000
Still time, though.

517
00:29:22,080 --> 00:29:23,600
CLARA: He looks like he's packing.

518
00:29:23,680 --> 00:29:25,480
He's been stranded for six months,
just met a time traveller.

519
00:29:25,560 --> 00:29:26,960
Of course he's packing.

520
00:29:30,560 --> 00:29:32,720
You can do it, then?
You can get me home?

521
00:29:32,800 --> 00:29:35,680
I just showed you, didn't I?
A test flight to a restaurant.

522
00:29:35,760 --> 00:29:38,480
Yes, but to my family, to my own time?

523
00:29:38,560 --> 00:29:41,360
-Easy! I can do that, can't I, Clara?
-He can, yes.

524
00:29:42,600 --> 00:29:43,720
Is everything okay?

525
00:29:43,800 --> 00:29:45,280
Yeah, fine. I'm fine.

526
00:29:45,360 --> 00:29:47,920
-Do I know you?
-No, nope.

527
00:29:48,880 --> 00:29:50,080
Is she doing the all-eyes thing?

528
00:29:50,160 --> 00:29:52,680
It's because her face is so wide.
She needs three mirrors!

529
00:29:52,760 --> 00:29:54,000
Doctor!

530
00:29:54,080 --> 00:29:57,840
We can't leave immediately, though.
The Tardis needs to recharge.

531
00:29:58,240 --> 00:29:59,520
Sorry...

532
00:30:00,840 --> 00:30:01,880
what?

533
00:30:02,640 --> 00:30:05,040
Overnight, that should do it,
shouldn't it, Clara?

534
00:30:05,120 --> 00:30:07,200
Overnight?

535
00:30:09,480 --> 00:30:10,960
One more night, that's...

536
00:30:12,360 --> 00:30:14,000
That's not a problem, is it?

537
00:30:16,720 --> 00:30:18,520
No.

538
00:30:19,480 --> 00:30:21,240
No, no problem.

539
00:30:25,600 --> 00:30:26,960
That's a shame, isn't it?

540
00:30:29,200 --> 00:30:30,560
What's a shame?

541
00:30:30,640 --> 00:30:33,040
DOCTOR: There's only three people left
in the universe

542
00:30:33,120 --> 00:30:34,800
and you're lying to the other two.

543
00:30:35,720 --> 00:30:38,360
It was the first thing I noticed
when I stepped in here.

544
00:30:38,440 --> 00:30:39,560
You must have seen it, too, Clara,

545
00:30:39,640 --> 00:30:41,280
-you've got eyes out to here!
-Seen what?

546
00:30:41,520 --> 00:30:43,320
The universe is dead.

547
00:30:43,640 --> 00:30:46,800
Everything that ever was
is dead and gone.

548
00:30:47,720 --> 00:30:50,280
There's nothing beyond this door
but nothingness forever.

549
00:30:51,600 --> 00:30:52,920
So why is it locked?

550
00:30:54,400 --> 00:30:55,440
Please...

551
00:30:56,640 --> 00:30:58,480
don't make me spend another night here.

552
00:31:00,320 --> 00:31:04,800
Afraid of the dark?
But the dark is empty now.

553
00:31:07,640 --> 00:31:08,680
No.

554
00:31:11,040 --> 00:31:12,360
No, it isn't.

555
00:31:15,320 --> 00:31:18,760
You'll be safe in here. Nothing gets
through those doors, I promise.

556
00:31:21,560 --> 00:31:23,000
And you two are going to wait out there?

557
00:31:23,080 --> 00:31:26,000
That would seem to be the plan.
Wait for what, exactly?

558
00:31:26,280 --> 00:31:27,560
Why can't we just leave?

559
00:31:27,640 --> 00:31:30,360
Like he said, it's recharging.

560
00:31:30,440 --> 00:31:32,320
You didn't look like you believed him.

561
00:31:33,480 --> 00:31:35,960
That's just how my face looks
when he talks.

562
00:31:42,800 --> 00:31:45,480
It's just a silly toy thing,
a family heirloom.

563
00:31:45,560 --> 00:31:46,680
Supposed to bring good luck.

564
00:31:46,760 --> 00:31:48,240
Right. Yes.

565
00:31:50,720 --> 00:31:52,480
Well, it didn't do
a very good job, did it?

566
00:31:52,560 --> 00:31:55,000
It did. You're here, aren't you?

567
00:31:55,960 --> 00:31:58,200
What were the chances
of you two finding me?

568
00:32:03,360 --> 00:32:04,520
Orson...

569
00:32:06,240 --> 00:32:09,720
do me a favour, take my advice,
when you get home,

570
00:32:09,800 --> 00:32:11,840
stay away from time travel.

571
00:32:12,160 --> 00:32:13,480
It runs in the family.

572
00:32:16,600 --> 00:32:17,720
What?

573
00:32:18,800 --> 00:32:20,920
Sorry. What do you mean,
"runs in the family"?

574
00:32:21,400 --> 00:32:26,160
Nothing. It's just silly stories.
One of my grandparents...

575
00:32:26,240 --> 00:32:29,960
-Well, great-grandparents...
-What is it? Tell me.

576
00:32:34,040 --> 00:32:36,040
You asked if you knew me.

577
00:32:39,840 --> 00:32:42,200
-It's a family heirloom.
-Yeah.

578
00:32:49,120 --> 00:32:50,440
CLARA: What are we doing?

579
00:32:50,520 --> 00:32:53,600
-Waiting.
-For what? For who?

580
00:32:55,560 --> 00:32:58,040
If everybody in the universe is dead,
then there's nobody out there.

581
00:32:58,960 --> 00:33:00,760
That's one way of looking at it.

582
00:33:02,280 --> 00:33:03,400
What's the other?

583
00:33:04,040 --> 00:33:05,680
That's a hell of a lot of ghosts.

584
00:33:08,080 --> 00:33:09,880
Do you have your own mood lighting now?

585
00:33:09,960 --> 00:33:12,240
Because frankly, the accent is enough.

586
00:33:17,360 --> 00:33:18,920
(CREAKING)

587
00:33:19,200 --> 00:33:21,440
-Where did that come from?
-It's always been there.

588
00:33:21,960 --> 00:33:23,360
It's only visible in the night light.

589
00:33:23,440 --> 00:33:24,720
But who wrote it?

590
00:33:24,800 --> 00:33:28,400
Colonel Pink. Apparently, at night,
he needs a reminder.

591
00:33:29,320 --> 00:33:32,800
Six months stranded alone,
I suppose it must be tempting.

592
00:33:33,440 --> 00:33:35,880
-What is?
-Company.

593
00:33:35,960 --> 00:33:37,240
(CREAKING)

594
00:33:40,120 --> 00:33:41,160
What's that?

595
00:33:43,160 --> 00:33:44,520
What kind of explanation
would you like?

596
00:33:44,600 --> 00:33:46,000
A reassuring one.

597
00:33:48,360 --> 00:33:50,960
Well, the systems are switching
to low power.

598
00:33:52,200 --> 00:33:54,280
There are temperature differentials
all over this ship.

599
00:33:54,360 --> 00:33:58,040
It's like pipes banging
when the heating goes off.

600
00:33:58,480 --> 00:34:00,640
Always thought there was
something in the pipes.

601
00:34:01,360 --> 00:34:02,880
Me, too.

602
00:34:04,360 --> 00:34:06,640
Who were you having dinner with?

603
00:34:08,640 --> 00:34:09,920
Are you making conversation?

604
00:34:10,000 --> 00:34:12,360
I thought that I would give it a try.

605
00:34:14,000 --> 00:34:15,760
(SIGHS) I told you. A date.

606
00:34:16,240 --> 00:34:18,560
-Serious?
-It's a date.

607
00:34:19,120 --> 00:34:20,520
A serious date?

608
00:34:21,280 --> 00:34:23,640
(LAUGHS) Do I have to bring him
to you for approval?

609
00:34:23,720 --> 00:34:26,240
Well, I would like to know about
his prospects.

610
00:34:26,720 --> 00:34:29,120
If you like,
I can pop ahead and check them out.

611
00:34:29,200 --> 00:34:31,320
Frankly, you've already done enough.

612
00:34:31,400 --> 00:34:33,120
(SCREECHING)

613
00:34:39,080 --> 00:34:41,080
Atmospheric pressure equalising...

614
00:34:42,640 --> 00:34:43,960
or?

615
00:34:45,440 --> 00:34:46,560
Company.

616
00:34:51,840 --> 00:34:53,600
Why are we doing this?
Why don't we just go?

617
00:34:53,680 --> 00:34:55,960
-Because I need to know.
-Why? About what?

618
00:34:56,040 --> 00:34:59,080
Suppose that there are creatures
that live to hide,

619
00:35:00,240 --> 00:35:03,280
that only show themselves
to the very young or the very old

620
00:35:03,360 --> 00:35:06,240
or the mad or anyone
who wouldn't be believed?

621
00:35:06,320 --> 00:35:07,960
-Okay...
-What would those creatures do

622
00:35:08,040 --> 00:35:09,080
when everyone was gone,

623
00:35:09,960 --> 00:35:12,920
when there was only one man
left standing in the universe?

624
00:35:13,080 --> 00:35:14,320
(METALLIC KNOCKING)

625
00:35:16,320 --> 00:35:19,280
-What's that?
-Potentially the hull cooling.

626
00:35:19,840 --> 00:35:21,600
-"Potentially"?
-Believably.

627
00:35:21,680 --> 00:35:23,160
(KNOCKING CONTINUES)

628
00:35:25,240 --> 00:35:27,920
-Someone knocking.
-(KNOCKING CONTINUES)

629
00:35:28,000 --> 00:35:29,040
Yes.

630
00:35:32,560 --> 00:35:36,720
Doctor, you don't actually believe
all this, do you?

631
00:35:37,160 --> 00:35:40,000
Hiding creatures,
things from under the bed.

632
00:35:41,480 --> 00:35:43,960
What's that in the mirror

633
00:35:44,960 --> 00:35:46,600
or the corner of your eye?

634
00:35:48,360 --> 00:35:51,920
What's that footstep following
but never passing by?

635
00:35:52,000 --> 00:35:53,360
(KNOCKING CONTINUES)

636
00:35:53,880 --> 00:35:57,280
Did we come to the end of the
universe because of a nursery rhyme?

637
00:35:57,800 --> 00:36:00,760
ETHEREAL VOICE: Listen.

638
00:36:02,320 --> 00:36:03,440
(KNOCKING INTENSIFIES)

639
00:36:06,400 --> 00:36:07,400
(BUZZING)

640
00:36:10,400 --> 00:36:11,400
(INHALES SHARPLY)

641
00:36:11,960 --> 00:36:14,640
-CLARA: That's you turning it, right?
-No.

642
00:36:16,680 --> 00:36:18,760
-Get in the Tardis.
-Why?

643
00:36:21,080 --> 00:36:22,360
I have to know.

644
00:36:24,360 --> 00:36:26,000
Doctor. Doctor...

645
00:36:27,040 --> 00:36:28,080
Tardis, now!

646
00:36:28,160 --> 00:36:31,360
Okay, okay. Somebody is out there.
Now we know we can leave!

647
00:36:32,080 --> 00:36:34,160
-Oh, Doctor!
-It's a pressure lock.

648
00:36:34,240 --> 00:36:35,840
Releasing it could've triggered
the opening mechanism.

649
00:36:35,920 --> 00:36:38,360
-Is there even an atmosphere out there?
-There's an air shell around the ship.

650
00:36:38,440 --> 00:36:39,480
Why are you still here?

651
00:36:39,560 --> 00:36:41,440
Because I am not
going to leave you in danger!

652
00:36:41,760 --> 00:36:44,720
Then you will never travel with me again
because that is the deal!

653
00:36:44,800 --> 00:36:48,000
Tardis, now! Do as you are told!

654
00:36:50,720 --> 00:36:51,960
You're an idiot.

655
00:36:53,440 --> 00:36:54,440
I know.

656
00:36:56,280 --> 00:36:58,240
-What's happening?
-He's opening the door.

657
00:36:58,320 --> 00:37:02,520
Perhaps they're all just waiting,
perhaps when we're all dead,

658
00:37:02,600 --> 00:37:06,000
out they'll come a-slithering
from underneath the bed.

659
00:37:10,440 --> 00:37:12,840
Oh, no, no, no, not now, come on!

660
00:37:13,040 --> 00:37:14,040
(STATIC)

661
00:37:16,520 --> 00:37:18,960
Oh! Always when it's important!

662
00:37:19,400 --> 00:37:20,720
(THUDDING)

663
00:37:22,000 --> 00:37:23,200
What's happening?

664
00:37:23,480 --> 00:37:24,840
(ALARM BLARING)

665
00:37:24,920 --> 00:37:25,960
What's that?

666
00:37:26,040 --> 00:37:28,760
The alarm. The air shell's breached.

667
00:37:30,240 --> 00:37:31,360
Stay here.

668
00:37:50,040 --> 00:37:51,080
CLARA: Is he okay?

669
00:37:51,160 --> 00:37:53,280
He's out cold. He'll be fine, though.

670
00:37:54,080 --> 00:37:55,680
Something hit him.

671
00:37:55,760 --> 00:37:57,360
Everything was flying out of that door.

672
00:37:59,520 --> 00:38:01,440
Could've been that.

673
00:38:03,480 --> 00:38:04,560
Yeah.

674
00:38:06,080 --> 00:38:07,440
What was out there?

675
00:38:08,480 --> 00:38:09,800
What were you so afraid of?

676
00:38:11,680 --> 00:38:15,120
I've been here a long time.
My own shadow, probably.

677
00:38:16,240 --> 00:38:17,720
-Yeah.
-(RUMBLING)

678
00:38:20,520 --> 00:38:23,800
That's probably just
the rest of the air escaping.

679
00:38:25,240 --> 00:38:26,760
You say "probably” a lot.

680
00:38:27,960 --> 00:38:29,640
(BANGING)

681
00:38:29,720 --> 00:38:32,280
We are safe?
Nothing can get in here, right?

682
00:38:32,360 --> 00:38:33,400
Probably.

683
00:38:34,920 --> 00:38:36,160
(HISSING)

684
00:38:41,160 --> 00:38:42,280
Have you got a plan?

685
00:38:42,360 --> 00:38:45,080
Telepathic circuits.
I left a trace in them before.

686
00:38:45,160 --> 00:38:47,800
-So?
-So apparently, that can do a thing.

687
00:38:47,880 --> 00:38:50,040
-That's your plan?
-It's not a plan. It's a thing.

688
00:38:50,920 --> 00:38:54,320
(WHISPERING) Okay. Come on, come on,
you can do it.

689
00:38:55,240 --> 00:38:56,920
-(GASPS)
-CLARA: Come on!

690
00:38:57,560 --> 00:38:58,600
Sorry.

691
00:38:59,320 --> 00:39:01,760
-(RUMBLING)
-Here we go!

692
00:39:05,560 --> 00:39:07,080
(MACHINERY HUMMING)

693
00:39:08,080 --> 00:39:09,400
Come on!

694
00:39:09,800 --> 00:39:11,720
(WHOOSHING)

695
00:39:12,240 --> 00:39:13,920
(THUDDING)

696
00:39:15,920 --> 00:39:17,000
Is that it?

697
00:39:19,880 --> 00:39:20,960
I don't know.

698
00:39:21,640 --> 00:39:22,720
I think so.

699
00:39:23,440 --> 00:39:24,520
Where are we?

700
00:39:24,600 --> 00:39:28,400
Somewhere else, I hope! No, no, no,
you stay, look after the Doctor.

701
00:39:28,480 --> 00:39:30,680
You can't go out there by yourself.

702
00:39:33,240 --> 00:39:35,120
Thing is, my timeline, it keeps on...

703
00:39:37,560 --> 00:39:39,520
Orson, you don't want to meet yourself.

704
00:39:39,600 --> 00:39:41,640
It's really embarrassing.

705
00:39:59,040 --> 00:40:00,320
(BOY SOBBING)

706
00:40:15,440 --> 00:40:16,720
(SOBBING CONTINUES)

707
00:40:33,920 --> 00:40:35,120
Rupert?

708
00:40:50,320 --> 00:40:51,880
(SOBBING CONTINUES)

709
00:40:52,520 --> 00:40:54,000
Orson?

710
00:41:02,080 --> 00:41:04,040
MAN: Why does he have to sleep out here?

711
00:41:04,640 --> 00:41:07,200
WOMAN: He doesn't want the others
to hear him crying.

712
00:41:07,280 --> 00:41:09,040
MAN: Why does he have
to cry all the time?

713
00:41:09,120 --> 00:41:10,240
WOMAN: You know why.

714
00:41:10,960 --> 00:41:13,440
MAN: There'll be no crying in the army.
WOMAN: Hush!

715
00:41:15,200 --> 00:41:18,200
MAN: Don't pretend you're not awake.
We're not idiots.

716
00:41:18,560 --> 00:41:21,960
WOMAN: Come and sleep in the house.
You don't have to be alone.

717
00:41:22,800 --> 00:41:23,880
If you can hear me,

718
00:41:23,960 --> 00:41:26,280
you're very welcome in the house
with the other boys.

719
00:41:27,280 --> 00:41:30,960
I'LL leave the door on the latch.
Come in any time.

720
00:41:32,160 --> 00:41:33,920
MAN: He can't just run away
crying all the time

721
00:41:34,000 --> 00:41:35,560
if he wants to join the army.

722
00:41:35,680 --> 00:41:38,920
WOMAN: He doesn't want to join the army.
I keep telling you.

723
00:41:39,000 --> 00:41:41,720
MAN: Well, he's not going to
the Academy, is he, that boy?

724
00:41:41,800 --> 00:41:43,440
He'll never make a Time Lord.

725
00:41:55,840 --> 00:41:58,720
Sontarans! Perverting
the course of human history!

726
00:41:58,800 --> 00:42:00,720
You're confusing me.
What? Shut up, shut up!

727
00:42:02,200 --> 00:42:03,200
Where's Clara?

728
00:42:03,280 --> 00:42:05,320
Clara! Clara!

729
00:42:07,280 --> 00:42:09,400
BOY: Hello, who's there?

730
00:42:14,960 --> 00:42:16,160
Hello?

731
00:42:25,000 --> 00:42:26,040
It's okay.

732
00:42:28,320 --> 00:42:29,520
This is just a dream.

733
00:42:32,040 --> 00:42:36,200
Just lie back again,
just lie back on the bed.

734
00:42:37,480 --> 00:42:40,800
It will all be okay
if you just lie down and go to sleep.

735
00:42:44,120 --> 00:42:45,960
Just do that for me.

736
00:42:48,080 --> 00:42:49,680
Just sleep.

737
00:43:04,600 --> 00:43:06,000
(SOBBING)

738
00:43:27,800 --> 00:43:29,000
Listen...

739
00:43:31,880 --> 00:43:34,600
What happened? What did you see?

740
00:43:35,280 --> 00:43:36,320
What's out there?

741
00:43:36,880 --> 00:43:38,720
CLARA: What if there was nothing?

742
00:43:38,880 --> 00:43:41,040
What if there was never anything?

743
00:43:41,880 --> 00:43:44,960
Nothing under the bed,
nothing at the door.

744
00:43:46,160 --> 00:43:49,800
What if the big, bad Time Lord
doesn't want to admit

745
00:43:49,880 --> 00:43:52,120
he's just afraid of the dark?

746
00:43:56,280 --> 00:43:58,880
Where are we? Have we moved?
Where have we landed?

747
00:43:58,960 --> 00:44:00,320
CLARA: Don't look where we are.

748
00:44:00,400 --> 00:44:04,200
Take off and promise me
you will never look where we've been.

749
00:44:04,960 --> 00:44:07,400
-Why?
-Just take off, don't ask questions.

750
00:44:09,360 --> 00:44:10,800
I don't take orders, Clara.

751
00:44:12,080 --> 00:44:13,160
Do as you're told.

752
00:44:17,280 --> 00:44:18,480
(WHOOSHING)

753
00:44:22,680 --> 00:44:24,920
-(GASPS)
-CLARA: Listen...

754
00:44:28,880 --> 00:44:30,200
This is just a dream.

755
00:44:32,280 --> 00:44:34,680
But very clever people can hear dreams.

756
00:44:35,400 --> 00:44:37,280
So, please, just listen.

757
00:44:39,920 --> 00:44:41,160
I know you're afraid

758
00:44:43,560 --> 00:44:45,120
but being afraid is all right.

759
00:44:46,400 --> 00:44:49,120
Because didn't anybody ever tell you

760
00:44:50,920 --> 00:44:52,480
fear is a superpower?

761
00:44:55,320 --> 00:44:57,720
Fear can make you faster

762
00:44:57,800 --> 00:45:00,040
and cleverer and stronger.

763
00:45:01,600 --> 00:45:05,240
And one day, you're going to
come back to this barn

764
00:45:05,320 --> 00:45:09,360
and on that day you are going
to be very afraid indeed.

765
00:45:10,600 --> 00:45:12,520
But that's okay.

766
00:45:13,280 --> 00:45:18,000
Because if you're very wise
and very strong,

767
00:45:20,080 --> 00:45:23,120
fear doesn't have to make you
cruel or cowardly.

768
00:45:25,000 --> 00:45:26,680
Fear can make you kind.

769
00:45:28,680 --> 00:45:32,160
No, no! Not the hugging! No, no, no.
I'm against the hugging, please...

770
00:45:37,240 --> 00:45:38,760
(DOORBELL RINGS)

771
00:45:44,200 --> 00:45:46,440
-I am so...
-I know.

772
00:45:51,760 --> 00:45:56,040
It doesn't matter if there's nothing
under the bed or in the dark,

773
00:45:57,280 --> 00:45:59,640
so long as you know it's okay
to be afraid of it.

774
00:46:00,960 --> 00:46:02,360
I just get nervous.

775
00:46:02,440 --> 00:46:04,640
-Me, too.
-I don't even know what I'm nervous of.

776
00:46:06,040 --> 00:46:07,480
I'll show you.

777
00:46:07,840 --> 00:46:11,760
So listen. If you listen to
nothing else, listen to this.

778
00:46:12,920 --> 00:46:14,560
You're always going to be afraid,

779
00:46:17,280 --> 00:46:18,880
even if you learn to hide it.

780
00:46:20,920 --> 00:46:22,560
Fear is like...

781
00:46:25,200 --> 00:46:26,920
a companion,

782
00:46:27,480 --> 00:46:29,360
a constant companion, always there.

783
00:46:31,080 --> 00:46:32,200
But that's okay,

784
00:46:33,440 --> 00:46:36,000
because fear can bring us together.

785
00:46:37,280 --> 00:46:38,760
Fear can bring you home.

786
00:46:41,800 --> 00:46:44,680
I'm going to leave you something,
just so you'll always remember.

787
00:46:46,680 --> 00:46:49,520
Fear makes companions of us all.

788
00:46:57,880 --> 00:46:59,960
ARCHITECT:
This is the bank of Karabraxos...

789
00:47:00,520 --> 00:47:03,280
Picture the thing
you want most in the universe.

790
00:47:03,400 --> 00:47:04,480
-(SCREAMS)
-(HIGH-PITCHED BEEPING)

791
00:47:04,560 --> 00:47:05,920
And decide how badly you want it.

792
00:47:06,000 --> 00:47:08,600
We're actually going to do it?
Rob the bank?

793
00:47:08,920 --> 00:47:10,880
DOCTOR: If we don't we die.

794
00:47:11,920 --> 00:47:13,040
We must locate them.

795
00:47:13,720 --> 00:47:14,840
PSI: (WHISPERS) What is that?

796
00:47:15,360 --> 00:47:17,000
DOCTOR: I don't know. Hate not knowing.

797
00:47:17,640 --> 00:47:20,000
Are you hungry, boy?

798
00:47:20,320 --> 00:47:22,360
DOCTOR: The bank is now open.

